DISCUSSION
In this article, we have presented waveguide elastogra-
phy for the evaluation of the anisotropic elastic parame-
ters of white matter tracts in the human brain using a
fusion of DTI, MRE, spatial-spectral filtering, the Helm-
holtz decomposition and inversions. We used DTI to
evaluate the pathways of the corticospinal tracts, MRE to
measure the dynamic displacements throughout an iso-
tropically sampled volume surrounding the tracts subject
to monochromatic excitation, applied spatial-spectral fil-
tering and a Helmholtz decomposition to obtain only
those wave components which were traveling along spe-
cific directions with respect to the fiber orientation, and
applied anisotropic inversions for the evaluation of the
elastic parameters. This method was applied to the CSTs
of five healthy, human volunteers ranging in age from 25
to 50 years, and obtained consistent results between all
the data. While every effort was made to provide consist-
ent measurements for all volunteers using a common an-
atomical target for reference, due to physical variations
in the cranial size and shape, the measured portion of
the CSTs will necessarily vary from person to person.
That is to say that 6 cm of the CST of one volunteer will
not be exactly identical to 6 cm of another volunteer in
terms of the portion of the CSTs within the FOV.
By implementing a higher order anisotropic model such
as Orthotropy, a lower order Hexagonal model presented
itself as a reasonable approximation by exposing redun-
dancies in the elastic coefficients and pure longitudinal
mode angles, and reflected the physical morphology of the
CSTs. Beginning with a higher order model in this way
alleviates imposing simplistic assumptions, a priori, in
the analysis of unknown media. It was further demon-
strated that there was a simple relationship between shear
wave velocity, longitudinal wave velocity, frequency, and
radius of the CSTs, similar in behavior to the vibrational
modes of thin rods, and that these longitudinal and shear
wave velocities were on the order of 5.7 m/s and 2.1 m/s,
respectively. Finally, it should be mentioned that wave-
guide elastography is capable of providing information
about the mechanical properties and integrity of nerve
fiber tracts in less than 20 mins, which is already feasible
in a clinical environment for addressing diagnostic issues.
Future research will apply this approach to other
white matter structures in the brain and other fibrous tis-
sues, e.g., muscle, as well as to anisotropic phantoms for
validation. Unfortunately, to date, no such phantom has
been successfully constructed, as it is difficult to build a
structure with sufficient water diffusion to provide sig-
nificant FA for DTI and tractography, while providing
adequate signal to noise and stiffness for a reasonable
measurement of the dynamic elastic displacements using
MRE. The construction of such a phantom that will sat-
isfy these criteria is currently under investigation.
Although we began with an Orthotropic model under
the initial assumption that this degree of anisotropy
exceeds that observed in human tissue, more complex
dynamical models may be required. Therefore, we will
potentially use other models appropriate for different
structures and investigate the use of multiple frequencies
such that dispersion analysis can be performed. In par-
ticular, as the longitudinal wave speeds within the CSTs
